# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2012-saarland-state-election
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1922-saar-parliamentary-election] Elections to the consultative Regional Council (Landesrat) were held in the territory of the Saar Basin on 25 June 1922.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1922-saar-parliamentary-election] The Centre Party emerged as the largest faction, winning 16 of the 30 seats.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1922-saar-parliamentary-election] Bartholomäus Koßmann of the Centre Party was elected President of the Landesrat on 19 July.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1924-saar-parliamentary-election] Elections to the consultative Regional Council (Landesrat) were held in the Territory of the Saar Basin on 27 January 1924.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1924-saar-parliamentary-election] The Centre Party remained the largest faction, winning 14 of the 30 seats, but lost its majority.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1924-saar-parliamentary-election] At its first meeting on 6 March, all parties except the Communists affirmed their continued loyalty to Germany.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1924-saar-parliamentary-election] Peter Scheuer of the Centre Party was elected President of the Landesrat on 24 March.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1924-saar-parliamentary-election] The election was held using the open list system, with each voter able to cast up to 30 votes.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1928-saar-parliamentary-election] Elections to the consultative Regional Council (Landesrat) were held in the territory of the Saar Basin on 25 March 1928.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1928-saar-parliamentary-election] The Centre Party remained the largest faction, winning 14 of the 30 seats.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1928-saar-parliamentary-election] Peter Scheuer of the Centre Party was re-elected President of the Landesrat.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1932-saar-parliamentary-election] Elections to the consultative Regional Council (Landesrat) were held in the territory of the Saar Basin on 13 February 1932.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1932-saar-parliamentary-election] Peter Scheuer was re-elected as President of the Landesrat.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1935-saar-status-referendum] A referendum on territorial status was held in the Territory of the Saar Basin on 13 January 1935.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1935-saar-status-referendum] Over 90% of voters opted for reunification with Germany, with 9% voting for the status quo as a League of Nations mandate territory and less than 0.5% opting for unification with France.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1935-saar-status-referendum] At the end of World War I, the Saar was separated from Germany and administered by the League of Nations.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1935-saar-status-referendum] France was given control of the Saar's coal mines.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1935-saar-status-referendum] After fifteen years of League of Nations administration, a referendum was scheduled to take place in the territory.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1935-saar-status-referendum] Towards the end of 1934, the League of Nations Council determined that a peacekeeping force would be necessary for the plebiscite period.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1935-saar-status-referendum] The German and French governments agreed to allow an international force to enter the Saar.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1935-saar-status-referendum] On 8 December 1934, the council unanimously approved a resolution calling for such a force.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1935-saar-status-referendum] Britain (1,500 troops), Italy (1,300), Sweden (260) and the Netherlands (250) agreed to provide troops for the 3,300-strong International Force in the Saar.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1935-saar-status-referendum] All expenses above and beyond those normally incurred for the same troops were charged to the League fund set aside for the plebiscite.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1935-saar-status-referendum] The League appointed a commander, British Major-General John Brind, with operational control of the force.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1935-saar-status-referendum] Troops patrolled, but did not police, the Saar.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1935-saar-status-referendum] They were not to respond except to emergencies and at the request of local authorities.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1935-saar-status-referendum] There was little to no violence during the plebiscite and the peacekeeping effort was regarded as a success.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1935-saar-status-referendum] While most political groups in the Saar initially supported its return to Germany, opponents of Nazism in the Saar began having doubts and misgivings after Adolf Hitler came to power.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1935-saar-status-referendum] Due to Hitler's oppression of their German counterparts, communists and socialists supported a continuation of the League of Nations administration, and a delay in the plebiscite until after the Nazis were no longer in power in Germany.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1935-saar-status-referendum] Roman Catholics were divided in regards to returning to German rule.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1935-saar-status-referendum] In order to achieve victory in the referendum, the Nazis resorted to "a mixture of cajolery and brutal pressure".
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1935-saar-status-referendum] In 1933, Sarah Wambaugh, one of the members of the Plebiscite Commission, stated that complaints of a Nazi "reign of terror" had been made by non-Nazi Saarlanders and by the foreign press.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1935-saar-status-referendum] The complaints included allegations that the Nazis engaged in intimidation, "espionage, secret denunciations, kidnappings ..., ... interception of letters and telegrams, [and] listening-in to telephone conversations", among other things.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1935-saar-status-referendum] In response, the Saar Governing Commission had to "promulgate several restrictive decrees for the maintenance of public order".
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1935-saar-status-referendum] In November 1934, fearing an armed intervention by France, which the German armed forces of the time would have been in no position to resist, the German government changed its tactics and reduced its belligerency.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1935-saar-status-referendum] Josef Bürckel, Hitler's commissioner for the Saar, banned the wearing of uniforms within a 40-kilometre (25 mi) zone along the Saar frontier between 10 January 1935 and 10 February 1935.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1935-saar-status-referendum] Burckel also banned meetings, parades, and processions in this area.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1935-saar-status-referendum] Jakob Pirro, the Nazi leader in the Saar, told his followers to obey the strictest discipline and implemented harsh penalties for any infractions.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1935-saar-status-referendum] Voters were outraged by the killings of two prominent Catholic leaders, Erich Klausener and Adalbert Probst, in the Night of the Long Knives.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1935-saar-status-referendum] A requiem mass for them drew large crowds, and a Catholic newspaper *Neue Saar Post* opposing Saar's return to Germany gained many new followers.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1935-saar-status-referendum] The Nazis made an effort to combat concerns about their anti-clericalism by appealing to the voters' anti-communism; pro-German newspapers printed pictures of atrocities from the Soviet Union, contrasting them to the "peace and prosperity" of the German Reich.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1935-saar-status-referendum] However, ultimately the National Socialists mainly focused on intimidation, with Nazi paramilitaries "threatening retribution to all those who might dare to vote against return to the fatherland".
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1935-saar-status-referendum] In the referendum, voters were asked whether the Saar should remain under League of Nations administration, return to Germany or become part of France.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1935-saar-status-referendum] To the surprise of neutral observers as well as the Nazis themselves, over 90% voted in favour of reuniting with Germany.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1935-saar-status-referendum] Every voting district saw at least 83% of voters support returning the Saar to German rule, and despite the claim of Georges Clemenceau (who had died in 1929) that there were 150,000 Frenchmen in the Saar, fewer than 0.5% of voters supported the annexation of the Saar by France.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1935-saar-status-referendum] The legitimacy of the referendum was questioned by foreign observers on grounds of widespread voter intimidation by the Berlin-sponsored Deutsche Front.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1935-saar-status-referendum] *The Sunday Mail* of Adelaide, South Australia, reported that the opponents of the Saar's return to Germany were "hounded off the streets and even blockaded in homes".
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1935-saar-status-referendum] Jewish shops were boycotted and vandalised, and Nazi supporters visited Jewish homes and demanded their voting identity cards in exchange for protection.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1935-saar-status-referendum] In his report, Marinus van der Goes van Naters stated that the Deutsche Front infiltrated public services such as municipal authorities and the police, and voters were forced to vote for Saar's return to Germany under threats of dismissals or loss of pension.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1935-saar-status-referendum] In addition, socialist and separatist newspapers such as the *Volkstimme* and *Volkszeitung* were taken down, and there were reports of illegal seizures and confiscations of documents by the members of the *Deutsche Front*.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1935-saar-status-referendum] Lewy Gunter believes that the result of the referendum could have been different with proper supervision, given the Catholic hostility towards the Nazi regime.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1935-saar-status-referendum] Following the referendum, the Council of the League of Nations decided that the Saar should return to Germany.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1935-saar-status-referendum] The Saar once again became part of Germany on 1 March 1935, with Josef Bürckel as Reichskommissar.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1935-saar-status-referendum] In 1936, it was incorporated into the Gau of Rheinpfalz (Rhine Palatinate) to form the Gau Pfalz-Saar (renamed Gau Saarpfalz in January 1936 and Gau Westmark in December 1940).
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1935-saar-status-referendum] Josef Bürckel remained the Gauleiter and, from 11 March 1941, Reichsstatthalter until his death in September 1944.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1935-saar-status-referendum] He was succeeded by Willi Stöhr who served until the end of the war in May 1945.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1935-saar-status-referendum] After the plebiscite, the Nazi authorities proceeded to clamp down on the Catholic Church's influence in public life, repressing and forcefully disbanding Catholic organisations.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1935-saar-status-referendum] Guenter Lewy reports that the prosecution of the Catholic Church in the Saar was even worse than in the rest of Germany, as the Reichskonkordat did not apply to the territory.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1935-saar-status-referendum] Even the part of Catholic clergy that campaigned for return of the Saar to Germany, such as Johann Ludger Schlich, was now forced to flee.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1935-saar-status-referendum] The report of General Brind on the Saar force recommended that in the future all such peacekeeping forces be assembled from countries with no direct interest in the matter at hand.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1935-saar-status-referendum] He noted that only a small force was necessary, since it was the moral authority of its presence that mattered.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1935-saar-status-referendum] Both observations are central to modern peacekeeping as opposed to collective security.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1935-saar-status-referendum] The Nansen International Office for Refugees was responsible for the successful settlement of the Saar refugees in Paraguay after 1935.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1955-saar-statute-referendum] A referendum on the Saar statute was held in the Saar Protectorate on 23 October 1955.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1955-saar-statute-referendum] The statute would have made the territory an independent polity under the auspices of a European Commissioner, to be appointed by the Council of Ministers of the Western European Union, while remaining in the economic union with France.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1955-saar-statute-referendum] Its rejection by voters was taken as an indication that they would rather reunite with West Germany.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1955-saar-statute-referendum] On 27 October 1956 France and West Germany concluded the Saar Treaty establishing that Saarland should be allowed to join West Germany as provided by article 23 of its constitution (Grundgesetz).
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1955-saar-statute-referendum] Saarland subsequently became a state of Germany with effect from 1 January 1957.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1990-saarland-state-election] The **1990 Saarland state election** was held on 28 January 1990 to elect the members of the Landtag of Saarland.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1990-saarland-state-election] The incumbent Social Democratic Party (SPD) government led by Minister-President Oskar Lafontaine was returned with an increased majority and continued in office.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/1990-saarland-state-election] The table below lists parties represented in the previous Landtag of Saarland.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/2012-saarland-state-election] The **2012 Saarland state election** was held in on 25 March 2012 to elect the members of the Landtag of Saarland.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/2012-saarland-state-election] The election was triggered by the collapse of the previous coalition government comprising the Christian Democratic Union (CDU) led by Minister-President Annegret Kramp-Karrenbauer, Free Democratic Party (FDP), and The Greens.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/2012-saarland-state-election] The CDU subsequently formed a grand coalition with the Social Democratic Party (SPD), and Kramp-Karrenbauer was re-elected as Minister-President.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/2012-saarland-state-election] After the 2009 state election, a Jamaica coalition (CDU–FDP–Green) government took office, the first of its kind in Germany.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/2012-saarland-state-election] The government collapsed on 6 January 2012 due to internal issues in the FDP.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/2012-saarland-state-election] Minister-President Kramp-Karrenbauer stated that "[a] credible and reliable cooperation is no longer completely possible in this coalition." The CDU held discussions with the Social Democratic Party in an attempt to form a grand coalition, but this failed, causing early elections to be called.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/2012-saarland-state-election] Having been reelected as the largest party in the Landtag, CDU was tasked with forming the government.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/2012-saarland-state-election] Minister-President Annegret Kramp-Karrenbauer said that she was seeking to form a grand coalition with the SPD, which have 37 seats altogether.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/2012-saarland-state-election] Both parties reached a coalition agreement on 24 April 2012.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/2012-saarland-state-election] The CDU and SPD would control 3 ministries each.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/2012-saarland-state-election] Kramp-Karrenbauer will also head the new government which will be sworn on 9 May 2012.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/2012-saarland-state-election] On 9 May 2012 Kramp-Karrenbauer's new government gained the vote of confidence with 37 votes.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/2012-saarland-state-election] There was 12 votes against and 2 abstentions.
[src:2012-saarland-state-election/2012-saarland-state-election] Her cabinet was later endorsed by the Landtag with the same number of votes.
